{{Infobox temple | name = Hindu Temple of St. Louis | image = HinduTempleOfSt.Louis.jpg | alt = | caption = | map_type = USA Missouri | map_caption = Location in Missouri | coordinates = {{coord|38.614725|-90.499097|type:landmark_region:US-OH|display=inline,title}} | other_names = | proper_name = | country = United States | state = [[Missouri]] | location = [[Ballwin, Missouri|Ballwin]] | elevation_m = | deity = | primary_deity_Godess = | utsava_deity_God = | utsava_deity_Godess= | Direction_posture = | Pushakarani = | Vimanam = | Poets = | Prathyaksham = | festivals= | address = | architecture = | temple_quantity = | monument_quantity= | inscriptions = | year_completed = 1991 | creator = | website = {{URL|https://www.hindutemplestlouis.org/}} }} {{Hinduism small}}
'''The Hindu Temple of St. Louis''' is located in [[Ballwin, Missouri]] and serves over 14,000 Hindus residing in the [[Greater St. Louis|St. Louis Area]]. The temple is located at 725 Weidman Rd, St. Louis, MO, 63011. The current [[Pandit]] of the Hindu Temple is Patabhi Maddipati
==History== The Hindu Temple of St. Louis was formally registered as a [[Charitable organization|Not For Profit Organization]] in Missouri in 1988. Groundbreaking of the temple commenced on April 21 1990 with a [[Puja (Hinduism)|Bhoomi Pooja]] and by November 8 1991, the temple was completed. The first physical deities were installed in 1995, replacing pictures of deities<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.hindutemplestlouis.org/|website = Hindu Temple of St. Louis|title = Hindu Temple of St. Louis|access-date = 25 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.archcityreligion.org/the-hindu-temple-of-st-louis/|title = Welcome to the Hindu Temple of Saint Louis|website = Arch City Religion|author = Ajla Ahmetovic|access-date = 25 October 2018}}</ref>. Mahatma Gandhi Cultural Center was the first building constructed in 1991. In 2000, several sculptors arrived from [[India]] to create ornate details on the [[Gopuram|gopuram]]. In 2008, Hindu Temple of St. Louis bought a nearby housing complex for $3 Million to expand the annex<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/hindu-temple-of-st-louis-expansion-plans-vex-neighbors/article_28812f3f-1699-592c-9cb3-0af1f0080c74.html|title = Hindu Temple of St. Louis Expansion Plan Vex Neighbors|website = St. Louis Today|date = 21 May 2011|author = Bogan, Jesse|access-date = 25 October 2018}}</ref>. This expansion sponsored criticism among local citizens due to the increased traffic, noise pollution and light pollution impacting the citizens that live adjacent to the annex. In 2012, the local subdivision and the temple reached a agreement to build a wall around its newly acquired land and a "15 feet setback"<ref>{{cite web|url = https://patch.com/missouri/townandcountry-manchester/hindu-temple-and-next-door-neighbors-come-to-an-agreement|title = Hindu Temple and Next Door Neighbors come to an agreement|author = Miner, Doug|date = 21 May 2012|access-date = 25 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.stlouischurches.org/west-st-louis-mo-churches/ballwin-mo-churches-63011/1303-hindu-temple-of-st-louis|title = Hindu Temple of St. Louis|website = St. Louis Churches|access-date = 25 October 2018}}</ref>.
==Campus== The temple currently consists of a worship place, a cultural center, reception area, a cafeteria, a library, a parking lot and a auditorium.
==Vandalism== In 2003, two vandals attacked the Hindu Temple with [[Molotov Cocktails]] impacting the front doors but caused no injuries<ref>{{cite web|url = http://pluralism.org/news/update-st-louis-hindu-temple-twice-vandalized-suspects-apprehended/|title = update st.louis hindu temple twice vandalized, suspects apprehended|website = Pularlism|access-date = 25 October 2018}}</ref>. The suspects were later apprehended.
