'''[[Muslims]]''' constitute 5 percent of the population of [[Trinidad and Tobago]], representing 102,421 individuals.<ref>https://www.indexmundi.com/trinidad_and_tobago/demographics_profile.html</ref> The majority live in [[Trinidad]] but there are a handful in [[Tobago]] as well. {{Islam by country}} [[Image:Montrose Masjid Trinidad.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A Mosque in Montrose, [[Chaguanas]].]] [[File:Masjid al Tawbah - Lowlands, Tobago, West Indies.jpg|thumb|right|Masjid al Tawbah in Lowlands, Tobago]]
==History of Islam in Trinidad and Tobago== The first Muslims to arrive in the country arrived from [[Africa]] brought as slaves by the colonists. The second group arrived in 1816 as a small proportion of those of the [[Corps of Colonial Marines]] who were African-born and had been recruited in 1815 in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] during the War of 1812, mostly settled in Fifth and Sixth Companies within the Company Villages near [[Princes Town]]. They were followed by African Muslims among disbanded members of the [[West India Regiment]]s settled between 1817 and 1825 in Manzanilla on the East Coast and in a group of villages south-east of Valencia, and further African Muslims were brought to Trinidad as a result of the [[Royal Navy]]'s interception of slaving ships following the [[Slave Trade Act]]s. From the 1840s, Muslims came from [[South Asia]] as part of the [[Indian indenture system]] to work on sugar cane and [[cacao plantation]]s. Muslims today are mostly of South Asian descent but there are converts from all races. In Trinidad there are Islamic primary and secondary schools. The first Muslim secondary school in the country, [[ASJA Boys' College]], San Fernando, was established in 1960. [[File:Masjid - Hermitage Village, Trinidad and Tobago.jpg|thumb|right|A Mosque in Hermitage Village]]
There are many [[mosques]] and [[Eid ul Fitr]] is a public holiday. There are several mosques belonging to the [[Ahmadiyya]] Muslim Community<ref>{{cite book | title=Ahmadiyya Muslim Mosques Around the World | page=319 | accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref> and 5 mosques belonging to the [[Ahmadiyya Anjuman Isha'at Islam]] Lahore. In 2005, an Islamic television channel [[Islamic Broadcast Network|IBN Channel 8]] was born. In 2006 [[Darut Tarbiyah The Islamic Network (T.I.N.)|Darut Tarbiyah - The Islamic Network (T.I.N.)]] was established.
==Notable Muslims== * [[Inshan Ali]] * [[Ben Ali (businessman)|Mahaboob Ben Ali]] * [[Radanfah Abu Bakr]] * [[Noor Hassanali]], former President. * [[Imran N. Hosein]] * [[Jamaal Shabazz]]
